                  },
                  "blocks": {
                    "richtext_qPriXF": {
                      "type": "richtext",
                      "name": "Richtext",
                      "settings": {
                        "title": "<h2><strong>Breaking Down Bioavailability and Nutrient Absorption.</strong></h2><p>Bioavailability measures how much of the consumed bioactives are available for absorption and can be used by the body. Once ingested, the effectiveness of supplements is largely determined by their bioavailability.</p><p></p><p>Bioavailability for most supplements’ averages only 16%-- meaning 84% is not absorbed by the body. The way bioactive compounds are digested significantly impacts their bioavailability, with three main factors significantly limiting absorption: </p><p></p><p><strong>Stomach Degradation</strong></p><p></p><p>Most nutrients are exposed to harsh stomach acid and digestive enzymes that break down or destroy a large portion before they ever reach the intestine.</p><p></p><p><strong>Intestinal Barriers</strong></p><p></p><p>To be absorbed, ingredients must pass through microscopic structures in the small intestine. Most supplements are too large, unstable, or poorly formulated to make it through.</p><p></p><p><strong>First-Pass Metabolism</strong></p><p></p><p>Even after absorption, the liver and kidneys rapidly filter and deactivate many compounds, preventing them from ever reaching the cells that need them</p>",
                        "text_alignment": "inherit",
                        "content_class": "richtext-md",
                        "text_color": "",
                        "custom_css": "& h2{\n   margin-bottom: 32px;\n}\n\n\n\n@media (max-width: 768px) {\n  & h2{\n    margin-bottom: 16px;\n  }\n}",
                        "hide_if_empty": "none"
                      },
                      "blocks": {}
                    },
                    "button_8FTpEC": {
                      "type": "button",
                      "name": "Button",
